4. Validation results (what was actually tested)
Optimisation objective throughout: Calmar (return / max drawdown), so drawdown is
weighted explicitly — not raw PnL or Sharpe.
BTC, TEMA_120, vol-target 40%, full period, with fees + slippage:

Final ~EUR 30,246 | CAGR ~50% | Sharpe 1.32 | Calmar 1.43 | MDD -35.3% | 40 trades
All-in reference: Sharpe 1.12 | Calmar 0.98 | MDD -51.5%
-> vol-targeting dominates all-in: higher Sharpe/Calmar AND lower drawdown.

Vol-targeting sweep (target_vol x vol_window):

Broad green plateau across target 20-50%, all windows. Chosen 40% sits inside it,
not on an isolated peak. 30% has marginally better Calmar (1.47) and lower MDD.
Train/test (lock 40%/30d, IS 2018-2022 vs OOS 2023-2026):
Sharpe OOS/IS 82%, Calmar OOS/IS 66% — both healthy (>60%).
IS-optimal target = 30%, the immediate neighbour of 40% -> consistent, not a
divergence. (A "NEE/verdacht" verdict in the notebook was a floating-point
artefact in the check, not a real red flag.)

Earlier robustness work (on TEMA_100, before switching to 120):

TEMA x ATR heatmap: broad plateau (TEMA 80-180, ATR 3.0-4.0). Chosen cell ~5%
above neighbour mean -> plateau, not peak.
Train/test OOS/IS ~102% (Sharpe) and ~101% (Calmar) — exceptional generalisation.
Bootstrap: 5%-CAGR -0.6%, loss probability 5.3%, 72.6% chance of beating B&H,
